Functional Mini Library

Short Description

You are to implement a functional library.

Estimation (h)

16

Topics

  1. Functional Programming
  2. JS Types

Requirements

  • Code style
  • No bundling and modules

  • The library should provide the following functionality:

    1) bool isArray(obj)

    2) bool isBoolean(obj)

    3) bool isDate(obj)

    4) bool isNumber(obj)

    5) bool isString(obj)

    6) bool isFunction(obj)

    7) bool isUndefined(obj)

    8) bool isNull(obj)

  • Working with arrays:

    1) obj first(arr)

    2) obj last(arr)

    3) newArr skip(arr, number)

    4) newArr take(arr, number)

  • Chaining: Implement the ability to create chains: asChain(arr).skip(func).take(func)

Custom jQuery

Short Description

Implement minimal version of jQuery using DOM API Methods.

Estimation (h)

40

Topics

  1. Document
  2. Browser Events

Requirements

  • Use only JavaScript DOM to access and manipulate the elements on an HTML document. Using of jQuery and other libraries that are intended to simplify interaction with DOM is prohibited.

  • Implement the following methods from the jQuery library:

  • addClass

  • removeClass

  • append

  • remove

  • text

  • attr

  • children

  • empty

  • css

  • click

Advanced Requirements

  1. Add more methods:
  • each
  • toggle
  • wrap
  1. Implement chaining functionality as at the following example:
$('.my-class')
    .each(function (index) {
        $(this).html('<b>' + index + '</b>')
    })
    .append($('div'))
    .addClass('my-super-class')
    .css({
        backgroundColor: 'rebeccapurple'
    });

Twitter Channels Search

Short Description

Create a Web Application to search Twitter channels and displaying their tweets.

Estimation (h)

54

Topics

  • Document
  • Browser Events
  • Local Storage
  • HTTP
  • JSON
  • XMLHttpRequest
  • Fetch API

Requirements

  • Use only JavaScript DOM to access and manipulate the elements on an HTML document. Using of jQuery and other libraries that are intended to simplify interaction with DOM is prohibited.
  • Create a Web application with an ability to search, add, remove and display Twitter channels as a list and displaying tweets for any selected channel. Use Twitter REST API for data retrieving.

Autosuggest search input

Implement an autosuggest search input which is updated on every typed character and provides the user with the result of the first 5 founded channels, an example:

Channel

Display information about every channel, an example:

  1. Each channel should have information about:

    • Name
    • Description
    • Number of tweets
    • Number of followers

  2. Channel can be removed by clicking the trash icon.

Tweet

Display information about every tweet, an example:

Each tweet should have a description and image (if attached).

Restrictions (do not apply to advanced requirements)

  1. Use only JavaScript DOM to access and manipulate the elements on an HTML document. Using of JQuery and other libraries that are intended to simplify interaction with DOM is prohibited.
  2. Use XMLHttpRequest Object to perform HTTP requests.

Advanced Requirements

  1. Use Local Storage to persist and display added channels after the page being reloaded.
  2. Use fetch instead of XMLHttpRequest across the application.
  3. Create a page of categories with an ability to add and display channels category. Implement the logic of binding a category to a channel.

Responsive Web Page Voyage

Short Description

Create a responsive HTML page using provided layouts for desktop, tablet & mobile.

Estimation (h)

40

Topics

  1. HTML fundamentals
  2. CSS fundamentals
  3. Understanding of RWD

Requirements

  • Don’t use LESS and SASS/SCSS. This task is to focus on HTML and CSS design, not front-end builds and preprocessors. They can be used only as a part of the advanced requirements.
  • Make use of HTML semantic elements.
  • Pay attention to container-content separation while designing HTML and CSS structure. It’s briefly described here.
  • Use BEM methodology of CSS architecture, but don’t follow it blindly.
  • Use BEM’s file structure. There are several options described, you will have to choose any but be ready to justify your choice.
  • The images extracted using Photoshop should be stored in a consistent format (JPEG, PNG). The choice of the format should be based on the image itself: for example, if it needs transparency, it has to be PNG.
  • Use PerfectPixel extension for self-checking on how close you are to the actual mockups. Bear in mind that there are cases when pixel-perfect makeup harms CSS readability and reusability. There are cases when it’s better to stick to some clear proportions/distances.
  • Though ultimately it may seem to contradict BEM, make use of either normalize.css or reset.css.
  • Use icon fonts or svg for icons. It’s recommended to use some tool to generate the CSS that you can add to your page (like icomoon) rather than use some cloud-based solution (e.g. font awesome).
  • Use similar fonts, available at Google Fonts
  • GitHub provides a simple static page hosting called GitHub Pages. This is convenient tool to check your results, use it.
  • Apply CSScomb tool to lint and order CSS rules. The general recommendation of ordering CSS rules can be found here. (basic configuration)
  • Test in Google Chrome, Internet Explorer 11 and Firefox.
  • The page must pass the content change test.
  • The main mockup contains a desktop version design. Additional design for mobile devices is also included.
    • The resulting HTML should react to the viewport changes. Page appearance must be consistent with the corresponding mockup.

    Advanced Requirements

    • Use less/sass as a style preprocessor (only after pure css is ready).
    • The page should have at least 90 points (in both mobile and desktop sections) at PageSpeed Insights.
    • All links, buttons and navigation should have hover, active and focus state.
    • Pictures must be adaptive and optimized.
